17/10/2006

 Croatian Prime Minister Ivo Sanader's visit to the United States included meetings with US President George W. Bush and top administration officials. Topping Sanader's agenda was Croatia's bids for NATO and the EU membership. 
*** 
Southeast European interior ministers gathered on Thursday (October 12th) for a two-day meeting in Budva, Montenegro. The focus was on progress achieved in the common fight against all types of organised crime, as well as on possible enhancement of regional and trans-border co-operation in the field. Representatives from Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Montenegro, Serbia and Slovenia participated. 
*** 
 Montenegrin President Filip Vujanovic visited Slovenia for talks with counterpart Janez Drnovsek. Both expressed their readiness to expand bilateral co-operation, and Slovenia offered to assist Montenegro's EU integration efforts and its bid to join NATO's Partnership for Peace programme. 
*** 
 Albanian President Alfred Moisiu met with Christopher J. Hoh, director of the US State Department Office for South East Europe on Thursday (October 12th). They discussed the situation in the region and latest developments in the Kosovo status talks. Hoh urged all parties in Albania to agree on electoral reforms, stressing the importance of holding free and fair local elections in compliance with democratic standards. 
*** 
 Turkish Cypriot leader Mehmet Ali Talat traveled to Brussels on Monday (October 9th) for three days of informal talks with European Commission President Jose Manuel Barroso, EU Enlargement Commissioner Olli Rehn and European Parliament President Josep Borrell. Talat was seeking an end to the economic isolation of Turkish-run northern Cyprus. 
